description.text: Optical Tramming Gauge Mount for accurate build plate leveling

Update 2-15-13:
I've been having trouble getting consistent results using the first iteration. I'm uploading another version that will allow me to use the leveling process included in the firmware. There's an arm on the side that depresses the limit switch, tricking the bot. This puts the sensor exactly where the extruder will be when it is time to print. Hopefully this will solve the consistency issues. I used a Keyence fiber-optic DIN rail amplifier (FS-V31C) and sensor head. I like the optical solution because it doesn't touch the build plate while you're working. I used some post-it notes on each corner so that I would get uniform reflectivity for the sensor head. I also put a single note at rear center just above the thumb screw. First, jog the printer head to slightly left of the the rear center and use a thin strip of paper between the extruder and acrylic to set the initial height. Don't use a business card, it is too thick. Ensure that your optical sensor is pointing directly at the post-it, and take a reading. Take readings and adjust at each corner post-it until all 4 readings are close to the same as the initial reading. It may be possible to mount the sensor head next to the nozzle using a FU-35tz.

title: Tank Track, Idler Sprocket and Hub

description.text:
More Tank stuff to go with Tank Track 2in and related parts to build a RC or Robotic Tank.
This is the idler sprocket that goes on the free spinning end of the track from drive sprocket. Uses 1/4"x3/8"x1/8" sealed ball bearings and 1/4" shaft with lock collar/spacer or 1/4" shoulder bolt. Use #4 sheet metal screws to attach hub to sprocket.
This is what started it all. An idea for a track tensioner to make a RC tank like the Howe and Howe Rip Saw Tank, that would allow the track to stay in place with long travel suspension and not flop around or loose tension when you hit bumps. If you watch the rip saw tank it just takes the bumps like they are not even there. This tank is a stable go anywhere platform for anything mobile.
Made the tensioner arm and shaft out of a long 1/4" bolt and some 1/2" flat steel with an arm welded to a lock collar and spring to keep tension on the track. Lock collar allows you to adjust track tension on bolt shaft. The spring has to be a stiff one, because when the tank backs up, the spring has to overcome the all of the weight of the tank trying to move in reverse. But you also have to give the track a little flex room to digest small pebbles that get in the track and sprockets in dirt.
Tensioner shaft goes through 1/8" aluminum frame with some bushings (1/4"IDx3/8"ODx1/2" long with flange) I found at True Value. 3D printed support for bolt in middle of tank with 1/4" bearings.
This was my second design. I placed the shaft further forward on the frame, and angled the arms back like other swing arms so the spring and tensioner would soften the first hit of anything the track has to go over at speed.
Would love to see any other ideas for ways to do a track tensioner! Have fun!
Added a hub cap for the idler sprocket. Use #2 screws, drill (2) holes in sprocket to hold hub cap.

The hub will need raft and support.
Sprocket will print without raft or support.

Jedoch hatte es 2 Jahre gehalten.
Habe nun ein neues gedruckt als PLA (weil's günstig ist).

Daher erst gar nicht damit ausprobieren! 2017: Rev.2
Das äußere Zahnrad wurde mit Taulman 910 Nylon gedruckt um Material zu sparen und um schneller Ersatz drucken zu können, falls wieder Zahne abbrechen.
Das Innere wurde mit PLA gedruckt, dieses verzieht sich nicht und lässt sich in hoher Qualität drucken was das einsetzten des kleinen Zahnrades viel einfacher macht.
Kein Spiel und kein Nacharbeiten. Bislang hielt das Zahnrad einem Härtetest stand (bis zum blockieren). Nachtrag:
Durch die mechanische Beanspruchung wird das Nylon weich und die Zähne können sich verformen. Sollte man einen ganzen Stapel schreddern dann maximal 2-3 Blätter.

title: Water Rocket Lunch base (base de fusée à eau)

description.text:
ENGLISH :
Hi, this is a lunch base for water rocket made of soda's bottle.
You need some little thing for fully made one (glue, bolt, elastic, gasket, string)
See instructions for complete description.
I wait for feedback and still open to made improvement ! ( diameter of bottle, various angle ... )
Thank you for interest.
FRANCAIS :
Bonjour, c'est une base de lancement pour fusée à eau fait avec des bouteilles de soda.
vous aurez besoin de quelques trucs pour la finir : colle, boulon, élastique, un joint torique et un câble.
regardez les instructions pour un descriptif complet.
J'attends vos retour pour l'améliorer ( diamètre variable, angle de lancement libre, etc ... )
Merci pour votre intérêt !

ENGLISH AT BOTTOM,
FRANCAIS :
J'ai proportionné les pièces pour s'adapter au goulot de bouteilles que j'avais. Vérifiez le diamètre de vos goulots et au besoin adaptez la taille du cylindre dans le puits.
Important : Il faut un joint torique pour eau/gaz qu'il faut insérer dans le puit, dans la gorge prévue. C'est lui qui fera l'étanchéité. Sans ce joint, la base ne marchera pas
Le montage nécessite une valve de pneu tubeless, un joint torique, un élastique, 4 boulons M6 avec rondelle et écrou, un peu de colle, du fil.
Il faut inserer la valve par dessous la base, collez la, puis refermer avec la pièce verte en collant pour assurer l'étanchéité.
Il faut monter l'anneau et les pièces bleues, puis fixer le tout avec les écrous sans trop serrer ( il faut que ca coulisse ). l'excroissance de l'anneau jaune doit être du coté du crochet rouge de la base. relier le premier trou avec le crochet grâce à l'élastique.
Reliez un fil assez long au deuxième trou, c'est la poignée de lancement.
pensez à sécuriser la basse avec des sardine de tente.
Merci du retour d'expérience que vous pourrez me fournir.
ENGLISH :
sorry for my english, if someone wants to correct me, you're welcome
Hi, keep in mind : dimension of bootle may vary between mine and your, so, measure bottle and adjust cylinder in the middle of base.
IMPORTANT : you need a torus gasket for water of good dimension to put in the gap made in the center cylinder. This gasket will make the base run. If you dont put gasket, your lunchbase will not work.
You need too : one elastic, 4 bolts, glue, tubeless valve, string.
put valve by bottom in the gap, glue for airtightness, put the green part in the gap and glue too for airtightness.
Mount the yellow and blues part, and bolt them, very lightly. parts must move between them.
Place the elastic between the first yellow hole and red hook.
Put a long string in the second yellow hole, it s the controle handle.
Place base on ground, and use big hook (for tent) to stabilise lunchbase.
Please tell me feedback. Thank you.

I found a bunch of old baby food jars and thought I could use them to store parts on a pegboard. So, I designed a model that would use the existing cap versus trying to make a threaded fitting. I prefer using the simple solution and fastened the original lids with 2 4-40 screws and nuts. The baby food jar lids were 50.5mm in diameter at narrow part (without lip).
This is designed for pegboard with 1 inch spacing. These fit perfectly into pegboard from Home Depot (see photo).

Settings (Suggested)
Raft: On
Supports: On
Infill: 35% Suggested to make sure 'tang' is strong.
Shells: 2
Layer Height: 0.20mm
After printing,clean up and remove raft and supports with an xacto knife. Be careful not to damage center 'tang' during cleaning. File as necessary for good fit in pegboard. Drill 2 holes through cap and fasten 2 screws with nuts (I used 1/4 inch 4-40 screws and nuts).

When I was modding my Robo3D printer, I came across some Z stabilizer designs..
All of the designs are fixed measurements.
This questioned me, because not any Robo3D casing has the same distance to the Z axis support rods, there is always some tolerance in measurement.
This can give some strain on the X/Z axis rods.
Therefore I designed a set of adjustable ones.
You will need the following hardware:
4x M4 bolt +/- 15mm
4x M4 nut
6x M4 ring

How they work.
  • Pre-mount the stabilizers
  • Raise the Z axis as far as possible to the top.
  • Then tighten the bolt in the slide mechanism.
    This way the stabilizers fixate themselves at the "correct" distances.

description.text:
When taking a shower, it is nice to set the temperature once. These tap/valve caps can be pulled out and rotated to the correct position so that the pointer faces up to indicate the right shower temperature setting.  
This fits into my 30 year old taps.

Remove the caps from your taps.  
Measure with calipers and adjust the scad file.  
Print two white ABS bases (which include the dot pointer).  
Print one red and one blue ABS cap.  
File out the holes as required so the pointer fits snugly in the cap.  
Put some acetone in the seams for a great seal.  
Climb into the shower and adjust the shower taps so that the temperature is just right.  
Snap in the caps with the pointers facing up.  
Enjoy.

title: bracket to mount sign on fire extinguiser frame

description.text:
Catchy title eh ?
So this is a little bracket thing to allow you to affix a sign onto one of those fire extinguisher frames.
Both my frames are 20mm diameter so I assume that is reasonably standard, scale accordingly to make other sizes.
The sign gets glued onto the flat area and the curved bit clips over the tube. It should be quite firm but it has been designed to also allow a jubilee clip to be put around it to hold it firm.
Mk1 was a bit weak so I added a support strut on the back of the flat part which stiffened it up nicely.
It can be used to attach anything flat to anything tubular I guess.

Prints on its side so no support needed.
I used PLA with 10% infill and 1 shell.
PLA will melt if it gets too hot, ie, in a fire, but these signs are not a legal requirement but an extra attempt to get people to remember where each extinguisher is.

title: Snake
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
(Alternate name: Articulated Python) When I was little, I had a wooden snake just like this (but better). The cutouts allow it to bend. So I thought I'd print out something similar to see if it would work. In PLA it is kinda stiff. A more flexible material would probably be better. I made the snake short so that it would fit on a Makerbot, so it came out kinda chubby. It could actually be a little bit longer and still fit. At some point I will design and post a longer version for RapMan/Mendel sized beds. Or maybe a modular snake! Oh and the STL has some weird stuff on the edges of the nose, but it doesn't seem to hurt anything when printing. Dimensions: 80.2mm x 80.2mm x 11.3mm tall
(It is printed diagonally, the snake itself is around 110mm long) EDIT (Feb 11, 2011) I've included an alternate file, SnakeThin.STL. This version has a thinner core that should be only a single layer thick. It ends up being much more flexible. Skeinforge kept giving me trouble with the core so I scaled up the model slightly. SnakeThin dimensions: 84mm x 84mm x 11.7mm tall

For each spike you want, decide how long you want it to be, customize the design, and print it!

I expect it to work acceptably on any printer capable of thin-walled structures, and it should look great any any transparent or semi-tranperent plastic.

I started with a 75 x 75 mm surface in the Sculpt environment in Autodesk Fusion 360 and manipulated the surfaces to create these mini worlds. Adding structures gives it some scale and let's you imagine exploring the buildings or river. The boats are printed separately and then attached after the river is painted. The layers in the print are just like the surfaces on a topo map. This was also an experiment in painting. I used a dry brush technique with Vallejo acrylic Model Color paints.

Infill = 10%
Layer height = 0.2

Feedrate = 40
